{"title_page": "The Revenant (2015 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2015 film directed by Alejandro Gonz\u00e1lez I\u00f1\u00e1rritu}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Revenant\n| image          = The Revenant 2015 film poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Alejandro G. I\u00f1\u00e1rritu]]\n| producer       = {{Plain list |\n* [[Arnon Milchan]]\n* [[Steve Golin]]\n* Alejandro G. I\u00f1\u00e1rritu\n* [[Mary Parent]]\n* [[Keith Redmon]]\n* [[James W. Skotchdopole]]\n}}\n| screenplay     = {{Plain list |\n* [[Mark L. Smith]]\n* Alejandro G. I\u00f1\u00e1rritu\n}}\n| based on       = {{Based on|''[[The Revenant (novel)|The Revenant]]''|[[Michael Punke]]}}\n| starring       = {{Plain list |\n* [[Leonardo DiCaprio]]\n* [[Tom Hardy]]\n* [[Domhnall Gleeson]]\n* [[Will Poulter]]\n}}\n| music          = {{Plain list |\n* [[Ryuichi Sakamoto]]\n* [[Alva Noto]]\n}}\n| cinematography = [[Emmanuel Lubezki]]\n| editing        = [[Stephen Mirrione]]\n| production companies = {{Plain list |\n* [[Regency Enterprises]]\n* [[RatPac Entertainment]]\n* New Regency\n* [[Anonymous Content]]\n* M Productions\n* [[Appian Way Productions]]\n}}\n| distributor    = [[20th Century Fox]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2015|12|16|[[TCL Chinese Theatre]]|2015|12|25|United States}}<!--- First release (premiere/festival) and countries of production per [[WP:FILMRELEASE]] --->\n| runtime        = 156 minutes<!--Theatrical runtime: 156:10--><ref>{{cite journal |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=revenant.htm| title=The Revenant | date = December 28, 2015 | publisher = [[British Board of Film Classification]] | location = London | accessdate= December 28, 2015}}</ref>\n| country        = United States<ref>{{cite web|title=''The Revenant'' (2015)|url=http://lumiere.obs.coe.int/web/film_info/?id=66252|website=[[LUMIERE]]|accessdate=June 23, 2017}}</ref>\n| language       = English<!--prevalent language only-->\n| budget         = $135 million<ref name=\"TheWrap\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/revenant-budget-soars-to-165-million-with-new-regency-footing-most-of-bill-exclusive/|title='The Revenant' Budget Soars to $135 Million As New Regency Foots the Bill (Exclusive)|author=Waxman, Sharon |date=October 16, 2015|work=[[TheWrap]]|accessdate=December 28, 2015}}</ref>\n| gross          = $533 million<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=revenant.htm |title=The Revenant (2015) |website = [[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=July 4, 2016}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''The Revenant''''' is a 2015 American [[Epic film|epic]] [[Adventure film|adventure]] [[drama film]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.20thcenturystudios.com/movies/the-revenant|title=THE REVENANT|date=March 19, 2020|website=20thcenturyfoxstudios.com|url-status=live|access-date=}}</ref> directed by [[Alejandro Gonz\u00e1lez I\u00f1\u00e1rritu]]. The screenplay by [[Mark L. Smith]] and I\u00f1\u00e1rritu is based in part on [[Michael Punke]]'s [[The Revenant (novel)|2002 novel of the same name]], describing [[frontiersman]] [[Hugh Glass]]'s experiences in 1823. That novel is in turn based on the 1915 poem ''[[Cycle of the West#The Song of Hugh Glass|The Song of Hugh Glass]]''. The film stars [[Leonardo DiCaprio]], [[Tom Hardy]], [[Domhnall Gleeson]], and [[Will Poulter]].\n\nDevelopment began in August 2001 when producer [[Akiva Goldsman]] purchased Punke's manuscript. I\u00f1\u00e1rritu signed on to direct in August 2011 and in April 2014, after several delays due to other projects, I\u00f1\u00e1rritu confirmed that he was beginning work on ''The Revenant'' and that DiCaprio would play the lead role. [[Principal photography]] began in October 2014. Location and crew concerns delayed the film from May to August 2015.\n\n''The Revenant'' premiered at the [[TCL Chinese Theatre]] on December 16, 2015, and had a [[limited release]] on December 25, [[wide release|expanding]] on January 8, 2016. The film received largely positive reviews, with praise for DiCaprio and Hardy's performances, I\u00f1\u00e1rritu's direction, and Lubezki's cinematography.<ref name=\"Stephanie Zacharek 2016, p54\">Stephanie Zacharek, TIME magazine, January 18, 2016, p54.</ref><ref name=\"MoraskiCBS_151225\" /><ref name=\"newyorkerreview\">{{cite web|last1=Lane|first1=Anthony|title=Wilder West \"The Hateful Eight\" and \"The Revenant.\"|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2016/01/04/wilder-west|accessdate=February 8, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"newyorkerreview\" /> It won three [[Golden Globe Award]]s and five [[British Academy Film Awards|BAFTA Awards]]. At the [[88th Academy Awards]], the film received 12 nominations, including [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]] and [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] (Hardy), winning [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]] (I\u00f1\u00e1rritu), [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] (DiCaprio), and [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]] ([[Emmanuel Lubezki]]). DiCaprio also won the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Drama|Golden Globe]], [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Leading Role|Screen Actors Guild Award]], [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Leading Role|BAFTA]], and [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Actor|Critics' Choice Award]] for Best Actor.\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- Per WP:FILMPLOT, summaries should be 400-700 words. -->\nIn late 1823, [[Hugh Glass]] guides Captain [[Andrew Henry (fur trader)|Andrew Henry]]'s [[trapping|trappers]] through territory of the present day [[Dakotas]]. While he and his half-[[Pawnee people|Pawnee]] son, Hawk, are hunting, the company's camp is attacked by an [[Arikara]] war party seeking to recover their Chief's abducted daughter, Powaqa. Many of the trappers are killed during the fight, while the rest escape onto a boat. Guided by Glass, the survivors travel on foot to [[Fort Kiowa]], as he believes traveling downriver will make them vulnerable. After docking, the crew stashes the pelts near the shore.\n\nWhile scouting game, Glass is attacked by a [[grizzly bear]] and left near death. Trapper John Fitzgerald, fearful of another Arikara attack, argues that the group must [[Euthanasia|mercy-kill]] Glass and keep moving. Henry agrees, but is unable to pull the trigger; instead, he offers money for someone to stay with Glass and bury him after his death. When the only volunteers are Hawk and the young [[Jim Bridger]], Fitzgerald agrees to stay for money, to recoup his losses from the abandoned pelts.\n\nAfter the others leave, Fitzgerald attempts to smother Glass but is discovered by Hawk. Fitzgerald, concerned that Hawk's loud reaction to him attempting to kill Glass could alert Bridger, who is away gathering water, stabs Hawk to death as Glass watches helplessly. The next morning, Fitzgerald convinces Bridger, who is unaware of Hawk's murder, that the Arikara are approaching and they must abandon Glass. Bridger protests at first, but ultimately follows Fitzgerald after the latter leaves Glass half-buried alive in a makeshift grave. He also leaves his canteen, in which he engraved a spiral symbol, with Glass. After they depart, Fitzgerald admits he lied about the Arikara approaching. When Fitzgerald and Bridger later meet Henry at the fort, Fitzgerald tells him that Glass died and Hawk vanished. Bridger is complicit in the lie about Glass's death, even though he knew nothing of Hawk's.\n\nGlass begins an arduous journey through the wilderness. He performs crude [[cauterization|self-surgery]] and eludes the pursuing Arikara by jumping into white water [[rapids]]. Bridger and Fitzgerald scout a pillaged Indian village. Bridger leaves some food behind for a lone survivor.\n\nGlass encounters Pawnee refugee Hikuc, who says that \"revenge is in the Creator's hands.\" The men share bison meat and travel together. As a storm approaches, Hikuc constructs a makeshift sweat lodge for a feverish Glass to shelter in. After a hallucinogenic experience in the lodge, Glass emerges to discover his wounds healing and Hikuc hanged by French hunters. He infiltrates their camp and sees the leader raping Powaqa. He frees her, kills several hunters, and recovers Hikuc's horse as Powaqa removes her rapist's genitals, leaving Bridger's canteen behind. The next morning, Glass is ambushed by the Arikara and driven over a cliff on his horse. He survives the stormy night by [[Disembowelment|eviscerating]] the horse and sheltering inside its carcass.\n\nA frightened French survivor staggers into Fort Kiowa and Bridger recognizes his canteen as Glass's due to the spiral symbol. Believing it stolen, Henry organizes a search party. Fitzgerald, realizing Glass is alive, empties the outpost's safe and flees. The search party finds the exhausted Glass. Furious, Henry orders Bridger arrested, but Glass vouches that Bridger wasn't present when Fitzgerald murdered Hawk, and was later deceived by the higher-ranking Fitzgerald. Glass and Henry set out in pursuit of Fitzgerald.\n\nAfter the two split up, Fitzgerald ambushes, kills and scalps Henry. Glass uses Henry's corpse on his horse as a decoy and shoots Fitzgerald in the arm. He pursues Fitzgerald to a riverbank where they engage in a brutal fight. Glass is about to kill Fitzgerald, but spots a band of Arikara downstream. He remembers Hikuc's words and pushes Fitzgerald downstream into the hands of the Arikara. Elk Dog kills and scalps Fitzgerald and the Arikara (having found Powaqa) spare Glass. Near death, Glass retreats into the mountains where he is visited by the spirit of his wife.\n\n==Cast==\n{{div col}}\n* [[Leonardo DiCaprio]] as [[Hugh Glass]]\n* [[Tom Hardy]] as John Fitzgerald\n* [[Domhnall Gleeson]] as [[Andrew Henry (fur trader)|Andrew Henry]]\n* [[Will Poulter]] as [[Jim Bridger]]\n* [[Forrest Goodluck]] as Hawk\n* [[Paul Anderson (actor)|Paul Anderson]] as Anderson\n* [[Kristoffer Joner]] as Murphy\n* [[Duane Howard]] as Elk Dog\n* [[Melaw Nakehk'o]] as Powaqa\n* [[Arthur Redcloud]] as Hikuc\n* [[Lukas Haas]] as Jones\n* [[Brendan Fletcher]] as Fryman\n* [[Grace Dove]] as Hugh Glass's wife\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n===Development and financing===\nDevelopment of ''The Revenant'' began in August 2001, with producer [[Akiva Goldsman]] acquiring the rights to [[Michael Punke]]'s then-unpublished manuscript.<ref name=\"Goldsman\" /> David Rabe had written the film's script.<ref name=\"DiCaprioCast\" /> The production was picked up by [[Park Chan-wook]], with [[Samuel L. Jackson]] in mind to star. Park later left the project.<ref name=\"Park\" /><ref name=\"HillcoatGone\" /> The development stalled until 2010, when [[Mark L. Smith]] wrote a new adaptation of the novel for [[Steve Golin]]'s [[Anonymous Content]]. In May 2010, Smith revealed that [[John Hillcoat]] was attached to direct the film and that [[Christian Bale]] was in negotiation to star the movie.<ref name=\"BaleTalks\" /> Hillcoat left the project in October 2010.<ref name=\"HillcoatGone\" /> [[Jean-Fran\u00e7ois Richet]] was considered to replace him, but [[Alejandro Gonz\u00e1lez I\u00f1\u00e1rritu|Alejandro G. I\u00f1\u00e1rritu]] signed on to direct in August 2011.<ref name=\"HillcoatGone\" /><ref name=\"InarrituOn\" /> Goldsman was also confirmed to be producing with Weed Road Pictures.<ref name=\"InarrituOn\" /> In November, [[Regency Enterprises|New Regency Productions]] joined to produce with Anonymous Content, and [[20th Century Fox]] was confirmed to be distributing the film.<ref name=\"EllisonTalks\" /><ref name=\"NewRegency\" /> Days later, I\u00f1\u00e1rritu stated that he was seeking [[Leonardo DiCaprio]] and [[Sean Penn]] for the two lead roles.<ref name=\"DiCaprioPenn\" />\n\n[[File:Alejandro Gonz\u00e1lez I\u00f1\u00e1rritu 2014.jpg|thumb|Director [[Alejandro Gonz\u00e1lez I\u00f1\u00e1rritu|Alejandro G. I\u00f1\u00e1rritu]]]]\n\nOnce I\u00f1\u00e1rritu agreed to direct, he began working with Smith on script rewrites. In an interview with ''Creative Screenwriting'', Smith admitted during this process he was unsure if I\u00f1\u00e1rritu would even be able to film some of the sequences they wrote. He recalled, \"He would have some ideas and I would say, 'Alejandro, we can't pull this off. It's not going to work,' and he would say, 'Mark, trust me, we can do this.' In the end, he was right.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://creativescreenwriting.com/i-think-he-wanted-to-toss-me-off-the-cliff-mark-l-smith-on-the-revenant-and-martyrs/|title=\"I think he wanted to toss me off the cliff.\" Mark L. Smith on The Revenant and Martyrs|last=McKittrick|first=Christopher|date=January 27, 2016|publisher=Creative Screenwriting|accessdate=January 27, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe film was put on hold in March 2012, as New Regency hired I\u00f1\u00e1rritu to direct an adaptation of ''Flim-Flam Man'', Jennifer Vogel's non-fiction book about her criminal father.<ref name=\"FlimFlam\" /> Penn was also under consideration for the lead role in that film.<ref name=\"PennFlim\" /> In December 2012, I\u00f1\u00e1rritu announced that his next film would be ''[[Birdman (film)|Birdman or (The Unexpected Virtue of Ignorance)]]'', a comedy-drama about an actor who once played a famous superhero. For his work, I\u00f1\u00e1rritu won the Oscar for Best Director and Best Original Screenplay, and the film won Best Picture. Filming took place in March 2013.<ref name=\"Birdman\" /> I\u00f1\u00e1rritu was scheduled to begin production on ''The Revenant'' after ''Birdman'' [[Wrap (filmmaking)|wrapped]].<ref name=\"Worldview\" />\n\nThe film was granted a production budget of $60 million, with $30 million funded by New Regency. [[Brett Ratner]]'s [[RatPac-Dune Entertainment]], a joint venture between Ratner's RatPac Entertainment and 20th Century Fox's former financing partner, Dune Entertainment, also funded the film.<ref name=\"EllisonTalks\" /> [[Worldview Entertainment]], who also co-financed ''Birdman'', was originally set to fund the film but backed out in July 2014 due to the departure of its CEO, [[Christopher Woodrow]].<ref name=\"EllisonTalks\" /><ref name=\"Worldview\" /><ref name=\"FoxFunding\" /> New Regency approached 20th Century Fox for additional funding, but the company declined, citing the [[Guarantee (filmmaking)|pay-or-play]] contracts made for both DiCaprio and [[Tom Hardy]], which would require that the actors be paid regardless of whether the film is completed.<ref name=\"FoxFunding\" /> [[Annapurna Pictures]]' [[Megan Ellison]] entered negotiations to finance the film shortly after.<ref name=\"EllisonTalks\" /><ref name=\"FoxFunding\" /> The Chinese company [[Alpha Group Co., Ltd.|Guangdong Alpha Animation and Culture Company]] partially financed the film.<ref name=\"financing\"/>\n\n===Filming===\n[[Principal photography]] for ''The Revenant'' began in October 2014.<ref name=\"Budget\" /> A planned two-week break from filming in December was extended to six weeks which forced Tom Hardy to drop out of ''[[Suicide Squad (film)|Suicide Squad]]''. In February 2015, I\u00f1\u00e1rritu, who shot the film using [[sunlight|natural lighting]], stated that production would last \"until the end of April or May\", as the crew is \"shooting in such remote far-away locations that, by the time we arrive and have to return, we have already spent 40% of the day\".<ref name=\"LongerFilming\"/><ref name=\"NineMonths\" /><ref name=\"FilmingEndMarch\" /> Ultimately, principal photography wrapped in August 2015.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\nThe film was shot in twelve locations in three countries: Canada, the United States, and Argentina.<ref name=\"FilmingSpots\" /> In Canada, filming took place in [[Calgary]] and [[Fortress Mountain Resort|Fortress Mountain]] in [[Alberta]], in Kananaskis Country west of Calgary, the Badlands near Drumheller, \nand at [[Squamish, British Columbia|Squamish]] and Mammoth Studios, [[Burnaby]], in [[British Columbia]].<ref name=\"FilmingSpots\" /> The scenes in the waterfall were filmed at the Kootenai Falls near [[Libby, Montana]]. While the initial plan was to film entirely in Canada, the weather was ultimately too warm, leading the filmmakers to locations near the Rio Olivia at the tip of [[Argentina]] with snow on the ground, to shoot the film's ending.<ref name=\"Budget\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/destinations/north-america/galleries/the-revenant-filming-locations-canada/revenant17/|title=The incredible filming locations for The Revenant|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nCrew members often complained about difficult shoots, with many quitting or being fired. [[Mary Parent]] was then brought in as a producer.<ref name=\"Budget\" /> I\u00f1\u00e1rritu stated that some of the crew members had left the film, explaining that \"as a director, if I identify a violin that is out of tune, I have to take that from the orchestra.\" On his experience filming, DiCaprio stated: \"I can name 30 or 40 sequences that were some of the most difficult things I've ever had to do. Whether it's going in and out of frozen rivers, or sleeping in animal carcasses, or what I ate on set. [I was] enduring freezing cold and possible hypothermia constantly.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/movies/leonardo-dicaprio-on-fighting-a-1281529422913590.html|title=Leonardo DiCaprio on Fighting a Bear in 'The Revenant' and Film vs. TV | author = Zakarin, Jordan | date=October 19, 2015|work=yahoo.com|accessdate=December 28, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2015/12/leonardo-dicaprio-jennifer-lawrence-joy|title=Leonardo DiCaprio Could Have Starred Opposite Jennifer Lawrence in Joy|author=Miller, Julie |work=Vanity Fair|accessdate=December 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\nI\u00f1\u00e1rritu had stated that he originally wanted to shoot the film chronologically, a process that would have added $7 million to the film's production budget.<ref name=\"InSequence\" /> I\u00f1\u00e1rritu later confirmed that the film was shot in sequence, despite Hardy's statement that the film could not be shot chronologically, due to weather conditions.<ref name=\"InarrituDefends\" /><ref name=\"NotInSequence\" />\n\nIn July 2015, it was reported that the film's budget had ballooned from the original $60 million to $95 million, and by the time production wrapped it had reached $135 million.<ref name=\"TheWrap\"/>\n\n===Visual effects===\nThe visual effects for ''The Revenant'' were produced primarily by [[Industrial Light & Magic]] (ILM). Other companies, such as [[Moving Picture Company]] (MPC) and [[Cinesite]], also created visual effects for the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.studiodaily.com/2016/02/vfx-supervisor-richard-mcbride-on-the-revenant/|title=VFX Supervisor Richard McBride on The Revenant - Studio Daily|date=February 19, 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\n{{Main|The Revenant (soundtrack)}}\nThe [[Film score|musical score]] for ''The Revenant'' was composed by Japanese musician [[Ryuichi Sakamoto]] and German electronic musician [[Alva Noto]] with additional music composed by [[Bryce Dessner]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Henry|first1=Dusty|last2=Geslani|first2=Michelle|title=The National's Bryce Dessner composing soundtrack for Leonardo DiCaprio's The Revenant|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2015/10/the-nationals-bryce-dessner-composing-soundtrack-for-leonardo-dicaprios-the-revenant/|website=[[Consequence of Sound]]|accessdate=December 6, 2015|date=October 20, 2015}}</ref> The main body of the score was recorded at the Seattlemusic Scoring Stage in the Bastyr Chapel in greater Seattle, Washington by musicians of the [[Northwest Sinfonia]]. Sakamoto conducted these sessions. Bryce Dessner's portion of the score was performed by the 25-piece Berlin-based orchestra known as \"s t a r g a z e\" under conductor [[Andr\u00e9 de Ridder]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gordon|first1=Jeremy|title=The National's Bryce Dessner and Alva Noto Joined Ryuichi Sakamoto on The Revenant Score|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/61726-the-nationals-bryce-dessner-and-alva-noto-joined-ryuichi-sakamoto-on-the-revenant-score/|website=[[Pitchfork Media]]|publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]]|accessdate=December 6, 2015|date=October 21, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Pitchfork2\">{{cite web|last1=Minsker|first1=Evan|title=The National's Bryce Dessner Shares \"Imagining Buffalo\" From The Revenant Soundtrack|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/62350-the-nationals-bryce-dessner-shares-imagining-buffalo-from-the-revenant-soundtrack/|website=Pitchfork Media|publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast|accessdate=December 6, 2015|date=December 2, 2015}}</ref> Additional licensed music includes \"Become Ocean\", the Pulitzer Prize and Grammy Award-winning work of [[John Luther Adams]] as recorded by the [[Seattle Symphony]] with conductor [[Ludovic Morlot]] and an excerpt of \"Jetsun Mila\" from French musician and composer [[Eliane Radigue]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soundtrack.net/movie/the-revenant-2015/|title=The Revenant (2015) - Soundtrack.Net|accessdate=February 7, 2016}}</ref> A soundtrack album was released digitally on December 25, 2015, and on CD on January 8, 2016. [[Milan Records]] released a vinyl pressing of the soundtrack in April 2016.<ref name=\"Pitchfork2\" />\n\nThe score by Sakamoto and Noto was ruled ineligible for the [[Academy Award]] for [[Academy Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]] at the [[88th Academy Awards|2016 Oscars]] as it was deemed that it was \"assembled from the music of more than one composer\".<ref name=\"Indiewire\">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/thompsononhollywood/the-revenant-is-not-eligible-to-compete-for-the-oscar-for-original-score-20151216|title=Why 'The Revenant' Was Not Eligible to Compete for the Oscar for Original Score|publisher=Indiewire.com|accessdate=February 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Documentary===\nThe film was accompanied by a 44-minute documentary, named ''A World Unseen'', highlighting the process of making the production. ''A World Unseen'' was released on January 21, 2016, on [[YouTube]]; both the date and medium of the documentary's release made it ineligible for the [[Academy Award for Best Documentary (Short Subject)]] in the same year as the film nomination.<ref name=\"20th Century FOX\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pJfTfsXFbLk|title=The Revenant: \"A World Unseen\" Documentary|publisher=20th Century FOX|website=[[YouTube.com]]|date=January 21, 2016|accessdate=February 15, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Gelbart\">{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/article/watch-experience-the-death-defying-revenant-shoot-for-yourself-in-44-minute-documentary-20160122|title=Watch: Experience the Death-Defying 'Revenant' Shoot For Yourself in 44-Minute Documentary|publisher=Indiewire.com|first=Bryn|last=Gelbart|date=January 22, 2016|accessdate=February 15, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Themes==\nIn the ''[[Los Angeles Review of Books]]'', film critic [[Wai Chee Dimock]] compared ''The Revenant''{{'s}} themes with those addressed in the literary works of [[James Fenimore Cooper]], particularly ''[[The Last of the Mohicans]]''. Dimock argues that the film re-interprets the concept of \"[[half-breed]]s\" from a derogatory idea that Cooper despised to an aesthetic way in which to see the world. She compared both works' protagonists\u2014Glass and [[Natty Bumppo|Hawk-eye]]\u2014as literary foils, with Glass living an inversion of the latter's biography and perspective.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lareviewofbooks.org/essay/half-and-half-inarritu-remixes-james-fenimore-cooper/|title=Half-and-Half: I\u00f1\u00e1rritu remixes James Fenimore Cooper|author=Wai Chee Dimock|work=[[Los Angeles Review of Books]]|date=February 16, 2016|accessdate=October 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the documentary of the film titled ''A World Unseen'', I\u00f1\u00e1rritu has stated that for the main themes of the film he revisits the issues and concerns of intense parental and filial relations, which audiences of his previous films readily recognize as a recurrent theme in his previous work. Regarding the theme of revenge seen throughout ''The Revenant'', I\u00f1\u00e1rritu has stated that the approach of vengeance seen in the film needs to be significantly tempered by anyone who would want to see vengeance as either an effective or useful moral to be applied in life. In the end, I\u00f1\u00e1rritu states, there can only be disappointment and lack of fulfillment for anyone who looks to revenge as providing a higher purpose for living or a life defining purpose.<ref name=\"20th Century FOX\"/><ref name=\"Gelbart\"/>\n\n==Historical accuracy==\n[[File:Cheyenne River IR.jpg|thumb|[[Cheyenne River Indian Reservation]] in [[South Dakota]]. Glass's survival journey did not take place in the cold season, nor did it involve tall mountain ranges.]]\n\n''[[The Guardian]]'' reported, \"The backstory about Glass's love for a Pawnee woman is fiction. It has been suggested the real Glass had such a relationship, but there's no firm evidence\u2014and no evidence that he had any children. ... As for the ending, it has been changed in one significant way: in real life, nobody got killed.\"<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/jan/20/reel-history-the-revenant-leonardo-dicaprio|title=How historically accurate is The Revenant? |newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=January 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nCanadian actor [[Roy Dupuis]] was strongly critical of the movie for portraying [[French Canadians|French-Canadian]] [[voyageurs]] as murderous rapists. Dupuis was originally offered a role as a voyageur, but he rejected it due to perceptions of anti-French bias and historical inaccuracies.<ref name=\"nationalpost\">{{cite web|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/arts/canadian-actor-says-the-revenant-completely-stupid-for-portrayal-of-french-canadians-as-murderous-rapists|title=Actor says The Revenant is 'stupid' for portraying French-Canadians as murderous rapists|author=Tristin Hopper|date=January 26, 2016|work=National Post|accessdate=February 7, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/radio/asithappens/as-it-happens-tuesday-edition-1.3420383/actor-roy-dupuis-slams-the-revenant-for-portrayal-of-french-canadians-1.3420388|title=Actor Roy Dupuis slams 'The Revenant' for portrayal of French-Canadians|date=January 26, 2016|accessdate=February 7, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.journaldemontreal.com/2016/01/23/roy-dupuis-sen-prend-au-film-the-revenant|title=Roy Dupuis s'en prend au film The Revenant|work=Le Journal de Montr\u00e9al|accessdate=February 7, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://quebec.huffingtonpost.ca/2016/01/22/the-revenant-reaction-de-roy-dupuis_n_9057998.html|title=\"The Revenant\", un film anti-canadien-fran\u00e7ais selon Roy Dupuis|date=January 23, 2016|work=Le Huffington Post|accessdate=February 7, 2016}}</ref> According to Allan Greer, the [[Canada Research Chair]] in Colonial North America, \"generally the American traders had a worse reputation than the Canadians.\"<ref name=\"nationalpost\" />\n\nI\u00f1\u00e1rritu has made a special point of emphasizing the importance of historical issues of ethnicity approached in the film and reflected in the mixed ethnic background of Hugh Glass's son portrayed in the film (portrayed as half Pawnee by Glass's wife) as relating to his own life and his identification with ethnic concerns. I\u00f1\u00e1rritu has referred to having encountered constant xenophobia and stated that: \"These constant and relentless xenophobic (comments) have been widely spread by the media without shame, embraced and cheered by leaders and communities around the U.S. The foundation of all this is so outrageous that it can easily be minimized as an SNL sketch, a mere entertainment, a joke ... I debated with myself, if I should bring up this uncomfortable subject tonight but in light of the constant and relentless xenophobic comments that have been expressed recently against my Mexican fellows, it is inevitable.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Evans|first1=Greg|title='The Revenant' Director Alejandro Gonz\u00e1lez I\u00f1\u00e1rritu Says \"Xenophobic\" Rhetoric Is No Joke|url=https://deadline.com/2015/11/alejandro-gonzalez-inarritu-saturday-night-live-the-revenant-1201614717/|accessdate=May 1, 2016|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=November 8, 2015|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nHistorians have also pointed out a number of anachronisms hinted throughout the film. One example of these is when John Fitzgerald talks about his father having friends in the Texas Rangers and about going to Texas and joining the army himself. This would suggest that Texas is either part of the Union or an aligned territory. However, in 1823, Texas was a sparsely-populated province of Mexico and therefore wouldn't have had an American army, let alone the Texas Rangers.<ref>{{citation|last1=Bradley|first1=Bruce|title=13 Major Facts The Revenant Got Wrong|url=https://truewestmagazine.com/13-major-facts-the-revenant-got-wrong/|accessdate=September 3, 2019|website=True West Magazine|date=May 12, 2016|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== Native American culture ===\nIn order to portray Arikara culture accurately, I\u00f1\u00e1rritu hired several cultural consultants<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://aptnnews.ca/2016/01/07/meet-the-man-who-taught-leonardo-dicaprio-to-speak-the-arikara-language-in-the-revenant/|title=Meet the man who taught Leonardo DiCaprio to speak the Arikara language in The Revenant - APTN News|date=2016-01-07|work=APTN News|access-date=2017-10-31|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/arianelange/leonardo-dicaprio-golden-globes-native-americans|title=Native American Groups Officially Respond To Leonardo DiCaprio's Call To Action|work=BuzzFeed|access-date=2017-10-31|language=en}}</ref> and teamed up with two linguists to provide faithful [[Arikara language|Arikara]] and [[Pawnee language]] lines for actors.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://archive.inside.indiana.edu/editors-picks/arts-humanities/2016-02-03-the-revenant.shtml|title=IU linguists provide Arikara and Pawnee dialogue for Oscar-nominated film 'The Revenant'|last=nolanb@indiana.edu|first=Bethany Nolan|work=Inside IU Bloomington|access-date=2017-10-31|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/dicaprio-wins-and-so-does-arikara-300228039.html|title=DiCaprio Wins and So Does Arikara|last=Conservancy|first=The Language|website=www.prnewswire.com|language=en|access-date=2017-10-31}}</ref> Hikuc, the Pawnee man who helps Glass survive, is played by a Navajo actor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:Y9oAWFHnRAwJ:https://indiancountrymedianetwork.com/culture/arts-entertainment/the-man-who-saved-leonardo-dicaprio-in-the-revenant-arthur-redcloud/+&cd=1&hl=fr&ct=clnk&gl=fr&client=firefox-b-ab|title=The Man Who Saved Leonardo DiCaprio in The Revenant: Arthur RedCloud - Indian Country Media Network|website=webcache.googleusercontent.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-10-31}}</ref>\n\nHowever, in one scene, a Pawnee character rescuing Glass is accompanied by a voiceover in [[Inupiaq]], which is spoken in Arctic Alaska, thousands of kilometres away and a different [[language family]] from [[Pawnee language|Pawnee]]. The voiceover was a recording of Doreen Nutaaq Simmonds<ref name=\"Doreen Nutaaq Simmonds\">{{cite web |author1=Mike Dunham |title=Barrow woman surprised to hear a familiar voice in 'The Revenant' - her own |url=https://www.adn.com/culture/article/uncredited-inupiaq-voice-featured-revenant/2016/03/11/ |website=Anchorage Daily News |date=11 March 2016}}</ref> reading a poem from a [[John Luther Adams]] recording; the words originally came from an [[Inuit]] woman named [[Uvavnuk]], an ''[[angakkuq]]'' (shaman) and [[oral poetry|oral poet]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/mar/14/the-revenant-womans-voice-used-without-screen-credit|title=Woman whose voice was used in The Revenant got no screen credit or money|last1=Gajanan|first1=Mahita|date=March 4, 2016|accessdate=March 15, 2016|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n''The Revenant'' had a [[limited release]] in the United States on December 25, 2015, including [[Los Angeles]]\u2014making it eligible for the [[88th Academy Awards]]\u2014before being released nationwide on January 8, 2016.<ref name=\"ReleaseDates\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Celebrity Extra|last=Elavsky|first=Cindy|work=Fort Myers Weekly|agency=[[King Features]]|date=October 7, 2015}}</ref> The film opened in Australia on January 7, 2016 and in the United Kingdom on January 15, 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Johnson|first1=Neala|title=British actor Tom Hardy says filming The Revenant was an education in endurance|url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/movies/new-movies/british-actor-tom-hardy-says-filming-the-revenant-was-an-education-in-endurance/news-story/63b150b821700501a8fa1119a38178de|accessdate=February 4, 2016|work=News.com.au|publisher=News Limited|date=January 7, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.screendaily.com/news/the-revenant-sets-uk-release-date/5096974.article | title= 'The Revenant' sets UK release date | author = Rosser, Michael | date = November 17, 2015 | work = ScreenDaily.com | accessdate=December 28, 2015}}</ref> In the Philippines, the film's release date was originally set for January 27, 2016, but it was eventually delayed a week to February 3, 2016.<ref>{{cite news|author1=philstar.com|title=WATCH: Leonardo DiCaprio in 'The Revenant'|url=http://www.philstar.com/entertainment/2015/12/11/1531516/watch-leonardo-dicaprio-revenant|accessdate=February 4, 2016|work=[[The Philippine Star]] |date=December 11, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=DiCaprio's film Revenant stays fierce|url=http://www.philstar.com/entertainment/2016/01/30/1547740/dicaprios-film-revenant-stays-fierce|accessdate=February 4, 2016|work=The Philippine Star|date=January 30, 2016}}</ref> Although studios initially chose not to pursue a theatrical release in [[China]], following the film's three wins at the [[88th Academy Awards]] on February 28, 2016, the film was granted a release in China but with several cuts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-china-revenant-oscar-leonardo-dicaprio-20160205-htmlstory.html|title=In China, no 'Revenant,' but mad Oscar buzz for Leonardo DiCaprio|author=Julie Makinen|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=February 5, 2016|accessdate=February 6, 2016}}</ref> It was released on March 18, 2016.<ref name=\"financing\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/china-clears-revenant-release-cuts-871323|title=China Clears 'The Revenant' for Release, Cuts Expected|author=Patrick Brzeski|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=February 29, 2016|accessdate=February 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\nThe [[DVD]], [[Blu-ray]] and [[4K Ultra HD Blu-ray]] were released on April 19, 2016 in the US.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Revenant (2015) Release Dates|url=http://www.movieinsider.com/m7509/the-revenant/releases|website=Movie Insider|accessdate=May 1, 2016|language=en-US}}</ref> Opening sales of the DVD along with on-line streaming orders placed ''The Revenant'' as number one in sales at Amazon.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Revenant (2015)|url=https://www.amazon.com/Revenant-Paul-Anderson/dp/B01AB0DVYK/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1461164144&sr=8-1&keywords=revenant+dvd|website=Amazon|publisher=20th Century Fox|accessdate=May 1, 2016|date=April 19, 2016}}</ref> Distribution to major rental outlets in the US was done on May 17, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=DVDs Coming Soon {{!}} Get Upcoming Movies on DVD & Blu-Ray\u2122 at Redbox|url=http://www.redbox.com/movies/comingsoon|website=redbox.com|accessdate=May 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Piracy===\nOn December 20, 2015, less than a week before its release, screener copies of ''The Revenant'' and numerous Oscar contenders, including ''[[The Hateful Eight]]'', ''[[Creed (film)|Creed]]'' and ''[[Straight Outta Compton (film)|Straight Outta Compton]]'', were uploaded to many websites. The FBI linked the case to co-CEO Andrew Kosove of Alcon Entertainment. Kosove claimed that he had \"never seen this DVD[s]\", and that \"it never touched his hands.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ricker|first1=Thomas|title=Hollywood's Christmas is being ruined by unprecedented leaks|url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/12/24/10663146/hollywood-s-christmas-is-being-ruined-by-unprecedented-leaks|accessdate=May 1, 2016|work=The Verge|date=December 24, 2015}}</ref> In October 2016, a former 20th Century Fox employee was fined $1.12 million in a separate case for uploading both ''The Revenant'' and ''[[The Peanuts Movie]]'' online.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.movies.yahoo.com/the-revenant-pirate-hit-with-112-million-fine-133256584.html|title=The Revenant pirate hit with $1.12 million fine|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''The Revenant'' grossed $183.6 million in the United States and Canada and $349.3 million in other countries for a worldwide total of $533 million, against a production budget of $135 million.<ref name=\"BOM\"/> ''[[Deadline Hollywood]]'' calculated the net profit of the film to be $61.6 million, when factoring together all expenses and revenues.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/03/the-revenant-profit-box-office-2015-1201721740/|title=No. 19 'The Revenant' \u2013 2015 Most Valuable Movie Blockbuster Tournament|author=Mike Fleming Jr|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 18, 2016|accessdate=March 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn North America, ''The Revenant'' opened in [[limited release]] on December 25, 2015, and over the weekend grossed $474,560 from four theaters in [[New York City]] and [[Los Angeles]] ($118,640 per screen), finishing twenty-third at the box office.<ref name=\"limited\">{{cite magazine|url=https://deadline.com/2015/12/star-wars-force-awakens-christmas-weekend-box-office-record-joy-daddys-home-concussion-point-break-1201672899/ |title='Daddy', 'Joy' & 'Hateful Eight' Reap Fortune As 'Star Wars' Halo Effect Impacts B.O...Can 'Force Awakens' Hit $1 Billion In U.S.? |magazine=Deadline.com| first1= Anthony |last1=D'Alessandro|first2=Anita |last2=Busch|date=December 28, 2015 |accessdate=December 31, 2015}}</ref> It was the second-biggest theater average of 2015 behind the $130,000 four-screen debut of ''[[Steve Jobs (film)|Steve Jobs]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2015/12/13/box-office-in-the-heart-of-the-sea-is-a-whale-of-a-fail-big-short-strikes-it-rich/|title=Box Office: 'In The Heart Of The Sea' Is A Whale Of A Fail, 'Big Short' Strikes It Rich|first=Scott|last=Mendelson|work=[[Forbes]]|date=December 13, 2015|accessdate=December 13, 2015}}</ref> The film earned a total of $1.6 million from its two-week limited run before [[wide release|expanding wide]] on January 8, 2016, across 3,371 theaters.<ref name=\"preview\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/01/the-revenant-star-wars-the-force-awakens-weekend-box-office-1201678383/|title='Revenant' & 'The Forest' Begin B.O. Journey On Thursday; 'Force Awakens' To Cross $800M This Weekend \u2013 Box Office|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=January 8, 2016|accessdate=January 8, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"box office\">{{cite magazine|url=https://deadline.com/2016/01/star-wars-force-awakens-the-revenant-leonardo-dicaprio-weekend-box-office-1201676277/ |title='The Revenant' Will Bear Through Box Office Weekend Dominated By 'Force Awakens' \u2013 Preview |magazine= Deadline.com}}</ref>\n\nIt made $2.3 million from its early Thursday preview showings from 2,510 theaters.<ref name=\"preview\"/> On its opening day, the film earned $14.4 million, ranking first at the box office.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2016/01/09/box-office-star-wars-the-force-awakens-falls-to-2nd-place-on-friday-still-topping-800m/|title=Box Office: 'Star Wars: The Force Awakens' Falls To 2nd Place On Friday, Still Topping $800M|first=Scott|last=Mendelson|work=[[Forbes]]|date=January 9, 2016|accessdate=January 9, 2016}}</ref> The film grossed $39.8 million in its opening weekend from 3,375 theaters, exceeding initial projections by 70%, and finishing second at the box office behind ''[[Star Wars: The Force Awakens]]'' ($42.4 million), which was on its fourth weekend of play. It was the director's biggest opening of all-time, and the fourth-biggest for DiCaprio and supporting actor Tom Hardy.<ref name=\"TheRev\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/01/the-revenant-star-wars-the-force-awakens-weekend-box-office-1201678383/|title='Force Awakens' Crosses $800M & Holds No. 1, 'Revenant' Takes No. 2 With $38M \u2013 Final Sunday|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=January 10, 2016|accessdate=January 11, 2016}}</ref> Critics noted that ''The Force Awakens'' had an advantage, considering that it was playing at 781 more theaters, that Sunday matinees are family-friendly, and since it had the benefit of playing in all North American IMAX theaters.<ref name=\"TheRev\"/> Nevertheless, ''The Revenant'' played very balanced across the U.S. and overperformed in all states except the Northeast region.<ref name=\"TheRev\"/> Its wide release weekend is among the top openings in the month of January.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/alltime/weekends/month/?mo=01&p=.htm|title=TOP OPENING WEEKENDS BY MONTH (JANUARY)|website=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=January 11, 2016}}</ref> It topped the box office in its fifth weekend overall and third weekend in wide release after competing with ''[[Ride Along 2]]'' in its second weekend. It added a $16 million in its third weekend, which was down 49.7% but topped the box office, despite [[January 2016 United States blizzard|a blizzard]] blanketing most of the [[East Coast of the United States|East Coast]] which reportedly hurt many films' box office performance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/news/?id=4148&p=.htm|title='The Revenant' Weathers Snow Storm While Weekend's Newcomers Perform as Expected|first=Brad|last=Brevet|website=Box Office Mojo|date=January 24, 2016|accessdate=January 25, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/box-office-winter-storm-jonas-858281|title=Box Office: Winter Storm Jonas Forces New York City, East Coast Theater Closures|first=Pamela|last=McClintock|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=January 24, 2016|accessdate=January 25, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/01/box-office-dirty-grandpa-the-5th-wave-the-boy-during-storm-jonas-1201688827/|title=Superstorm 2016 \u2013 Box Office Iced Out Of About 8% To 10% In Receipts|first=Anita|last=Busch|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=January 24, 2016|accessdate=January 25, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ew.com/article/2016/01/28/box-office-preview-kung-fu-panda-3-finest-hours-fifty-shades-of-black|title=Box office preview: Kung Fu Panda 3 eyes $40+ million opening|author=Devan Coggan|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=January 28, 2016|accessdate=January 29, 2016}}</ref> The following weekend it was overtaken by Fox's own animated movie ''[[Kung Fu Panda 3]]'' thereby topping the box office for one weekend.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/box-office-kung-fu-panda-860921|title=Box Office: 'Kung Fu Panda 3' No. 1 With $41M; 'Finest Hours,' 'Fifty Shades of Black' Sink|author=Pamela McClintock|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=January 31, 2016|accessdate=January 31, 2016}}</ref> Following the announcement of the Oscar nominees on January 14, ''The Revenant'' witnessed the biggest boost among the Best Picture category, jumping from $54.1 million to $170.5 million, an increase of +215% up to the Oscar ceremony in the weekend ending February 28.<ref name=\"Boost\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/02/spotlight-the-revenant-best-picture-box-office-boost-1201710795/|title='Spotlight's Surprise Best Picture Win At The Oscars: What Does This Mean For Its Box Office?|author=Anthony D'Alessandro|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=February 28, 2016|accessdate=February 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOutside North America, the film secured a release in 78 countries.<ref name=\"Overseas3rdOpening\"/> It made $20.5 million from 2,407 screens in just 18 markets, placing behind ''The Force Awakens'' at the international box office chart and first among newly released films.<ref name=\"Overseas2ndOpening\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/01/revenant-hateful-eight-star-wars-force-awakens-sherlock-international-box-office-weekend-results-1201679472/|title='Revenant' Rides To $20.5M Overseas, 'Hateful 8' Takes $17M, 'Star Wars' Eyes $1B \u2013 Intl Box Office Update|first=Nancy|last=Tartaglione|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=January 11, 2016|accessdate=January 12, 2016}}</ref> The following weekend, it added $32.3 million from 25 markets on 4,849 screens.<ref name=\"Overseas3rdOpening\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/01/revenant-5th-wave-hateful-8-ride-along-2-star-wars-international-box-office-weekend-results-1201684764/|title='Force Awakens' $100M In China; Oscar Fave 'The Revenant' Opens Big In UK, Korea \u2013 Intl B.O. Update|author=Nancy Tartaglione, Anita Busch|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=January 19, 2016|accessdate=January 21, 2015}}</ref> The film topped the international box office in its third weekend\u2014the same weekend when it topped the U.S. box office\u2014overtaking ''The Force Awakens'' with $33.7 million from 48 markets.<ref name=\"Overseas4thOpening\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/01/star-wars-the-force-awakens-kung-fu-panda-3-revenant-5th-wave-dirty-grandpa-big-short-overseas-box-office-weekend-1201689456/|title='The Revenant' Tops Offshore Weekend With $33.8M And Over $223M Global; 'The Force Awakens' At #2 \u2013 Intl Box Office Final|first=Nancy|last=Tartaglione|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=January 25, 2016|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref> In the United Kingdom and Ireland, it took the No. 1 spot with $7.87 million or \u00a35.2 million ($7.4 million) from 589 theaters and remained there for a second weekend declining by 24% with \u00a33.86 million ($5.5 million), as well as for a third weekend.<ref name=\"Overseas3rdOpening\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/jan/20/the-revenant-attacks-star-wars-uk-box-office-rocky-spinoff-creed|title=The Revenant attacks Star Wars in rise to top of UK box office|first=Charles|last=Gant|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=January 20, 2016|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/jan/26/the-revenant-mauls-uk-box-office-competition-ride-along-2-the-big-short|title=The Revenant mauls UK box office but Sandra Bullock's brand may be in crisis|author=Charles Gant|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=January 26, 2016|accessdate=January 29, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Overseas5thOpening\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/01/kung-fu-panda-3-china-revenant-star-wars-spotlight-international-box-office-overseas-weekend-results-1201693811/|title='Kung Fu Panda 3' Kicks Off With $75.7M; 'Ten Commandments' Eyes Brazil Record \u2013 Intl B.O. Final|author=Nancy Tartaglione|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=February 2, 2016|accessdate=February 2, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"UKFeb2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/feb/02/uk-box-office-revenant-martian-leonardo-dicaprio-matt-damon|title=Dirty Grandpa cleans up at UK box office as The Revenant still clings to top spot|author=Charles Gant|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=February 2, 2016|accessdate=February 3, 2016}}</ref> Similarly, in Russia, it passed ''The Force Awakens'' to take the top spot with $7.5 million from 1,063 screens.<ref name=\"Overseas2ndOpening\"/> In France, it has the biggest opening day in Paris and the third biggest opening weekend of 2016 with $8.2 million.<ref name=\"Overseas9thOpening\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/02/gods-of-egypt-deadpool-zootopia-mermaid-international-box-office-overseas-weekend-resuts-1201710506/|title='Deadpool' At $609M Global; 'Gods Of Egypt' Bows To $24M, 'Zootopia' Lands $33M 3rd Frame \u2013 Int'l B.O. Final|author=Nancy Tartaglione|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=February 28, 2016|accessdate=March 1, 2016}}</ref> It also opened at No. 1 in Mexico ($5.1 million), Spain ($4 million), the Netherlands ($1.3 million), Belgium ($1.1 million), Argentina ($955,000), Sweden ($914,000), South Korea, Denmark, Norway, Israel, Egypt and Portugal among other markets.<ref name=\"Overseas3rdOpening\"/><ref name=\"Overseas4thOpening\"/><ref name=\"Overseas5thOpening\"/><ref name=\"Overseas6thOpening\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/02/revenant-kung-fu-panda-star-wars-force-awakens-martian-international-box-office-weekend-results-1201697966/|title='Revenant', 'Martian' Land New Global Milestones; 'Kung Fu Panda 3' Tops $100M In China \u2013 Intl Box Office|author=Nancy Tartaglione|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=February 7, 2016|accessdate=February 8, 2016}}</ref> In Germany ($4.6 million) and Australia ($2.9 million), it debuted at No. 2 both behind ''The Force Awakens'' and in Brazil ($2.17 million) behind ''The Ten Commandments''.<ref name=\"Overseas2ndOpening\"/><ref name=\"Overseas6thOpening\"/> It had one of the top ten openings of all time for a Fox film, not accounting for inflation in South Korea with $5.7 million and went on to top the box office there for a second weekend with $3.22 million despite cold weather affecting theater attendance resulting in low box office performance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/south-korea-box-office-revenant-856647|title=South Korea Box Office: 'The Revenant' Among Top Fox Openings of All Time|author=Lee Hyo-won|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=January 18, 2016|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/south-korea-box-office-revenant-858872|title=South Korea Box Office: 'The Revenant' Top for Second Week Despite Bitterly Cold Weather|author=Lee Hyo-won|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=January 25, 2016|accessdate=January 16, 2016}}</ref> In Russia, despite not opening at No. 1, it topped the box office in its second weekend with $4.4 million\u2014more than ''The Force Awakens''\u2014and went on to top for a third weekend with $3.6 million.<ref name=\"Overseas3rdOpening\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/german-box-office-revenant-tops-858888|title=German Box Office: 'The Revenant' Stays on Top in Third Weekend|first=Scott|last=Roxborough|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=January 25, 2016|accessdate=January 26, 2016}}</ref> In China it had an opening day of around $11 million from more than 11,000 screens, including $250,000 in midnight previews, and $23 million in two days.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/robcain/2016/03/18/revenant-soars-eddie-the-eagle-crashes-on-china-opening-day/#74871bf32d04|title='Revenant' Soars, 'Eddie the Eagle' Crashes on China Opening Day|author=Rob Cain|work=[[Forbes]]|date=March 18, 2016|accessdate=March 20, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/robcain/2016/03/17/can-leonardo-conquer-china-again-with-revenant/#61798d62775f|title=Can Leonardo DiCaprio Conquer China Again With 'Revenant'?|author=Rob Cain|work=[[Forbes]]|date=March 17, 2016|accessdate=March 20, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/03/the-revenant-china-box-office-opening-weekend-leonardo-dicaprio-1201723193/|title='The Revenant' Traps Big China Bow; $30M+ Opening Weekend In Sights|author=Nancy Tartaglione|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 19, 2016|accessdate=March 20, 2016}}</ref> In its opening weekend, it grossed $31 million, coming in second place behind the animated ''[[Zootopia]]''. IMAX comprised $2.3 million on 278 screens.<ref name=\"Overseas13thOpening\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/03/zootopia-allegiant-divergent-revenant-kung-fu-panda-international-box-office-weekend-resultsinternational-box-office-1201723288/|title='Zootopia' A Flash Away From $600M WW; China Welcomes 'The Revenant' With $31M Bow \u2013 Intl B.O. Final|author=Nancy Tartaglione|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 21, 2016|accessdate=March 21, 2016}}</ref> In terms of total earnings, its largest markets outside of the U.S. and Canada are China ($58.6 million), the United Kingdom ($32.8 million), Germany ($28.7 million) and France ($28.2 million).<ref name=\"Overseas8thOpening\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/02/deadpool-zootopia-mermaid-hail-caesar-international-box-office-overseas-weekend-results-1201706617/|title='Deadpool' Scores $85.3M In 2nd Offshore Frame; Nears $500M Global \u2013 Intl Box Office|author=Nancy Tartaglione|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=February 21, 2016|accessdate=February 22, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Overseas14thOpening\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/03/batman-v-superman-dawn-of-justice-zootopia-greek-wedding-revenant-international-box-office-results-1201726990/|title='Zootopia' Nears $700M Global, Crosses $200M In China \u2013 International Box Office|author=Nancy Tartaglione|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=March 27, 2016|accessdate=March 27, 2016}}</ref> The film opened in Japan on March 23.<ref name=\"Overseas9thOpening\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-film-revenant-dicaprio/dicaprio-brings-the-revenant-to-japan-idUSKCN0WP2P3|title=Dicaprio brings 'The Revenant' to Japan|date=March 24, 2016|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film has an approval rating of 79%, based on 386 reviews, with an [[average rating]] of 7.85/10. The website's critical consensus reads: \"As starkly beautiful as it is harshly uncompromising, ''The Revenant'' uses Leonardo DiCaprio's committed performance as fuel for an absorbing drama that offers punishing challenges \u2014 and rich rewards.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_revenant_2015/ |title=The Revenant (2015) |work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] |accessdate=October 25, 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film has a [[weighted average]] score of 76 out of 100, based on 50 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-revenant-2015 |title=The Revenant Reviews |work=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=January 19, 2016}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film an average grade of \"B+\" on an A+ to F scale, while [[PostTrak]] reported audiences gave it an overall positive score of 85% and a 59% \"definite recommend\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pbs.twimg.com/media/CYQ4dFZUQAAKrts.jpg |title=CinemaScore |work=cinemascore.com |via=[[Twitter]]}}</ref><ref name=\"CinemaScore\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/01/the-revenant-star-wars-the-force-awakens-weekend-box-office-1201678383/ |title='Force Awakens' Crosses $800M On Saturday & Holds No. 1, 'Revenant' Taking No. 2 With $38M |website=Deadline Hollywood}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Tom Hardy Cannes 2015.jpg|thumb|left|170px|[[Tom Hardy]] received strong praise for his performance as John Fitzgerald.]]\n\nReviewers cited in a ''CBS News'' survey of critics highly praised DiCaprio's performance, referring to it as an \"astonishing testament to his commitment to a role\" and as an \"anchoring performance of ferocious 200 percent commitment.\"<ref name = MoraskiCBS_151225>{{cite web | author = Moraski, Lauren | date = December 25, 2015 | title = \"The Revenant\" Reviews: What Critics Are Saying About Leonardo DiCaprio's Latest Film | url = https://www.cbsnews.com/news/the-revenant-reviews-what-critics-are-saying-about-leonardo-dicaprio-latest-movie/ | access-date = December 28, 2015 | work = CBS News }}</ref> [[Peter Travers]] of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' called DiCaprio's acting \"a virtuoso performance, thrilling in its brute force and silent eloquence.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/the-revenant-20151222?page=2|title=Page 2 of 'The Revenant' Movie Review - Rolling Stone|first=Peter|last=Travers|date=December 22, 2015|work=Rolling Stone|accessdate=December 28, 2015}}</ref> Writing for ''[[NY Magazine]]''/''Vulture'', David Edelstein called the film a \"tour de force\" and \"[b]leak as hell but considerably more beautiful,\" but noted the film had \"traditional masculinity instead of a search for what illuminates man's inhumanity to man.\"\n\nJustin Chang of ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' wrote I\u00f1\u00e1rritu \"increasingly succumbs to the air of grim overdetermination that has marred much of [his] past work\" and it was \"an imposing vision... but also an inflated and emotionally stunted one.\"<ref name = MoraskiCBS_151225/> Stephanie Zacharek, writing for ''TIME'' magazine, gave a positive review to the film stating: \"Inarritu may have fashioned ''The Revenant'' as the ultimate endurance test, but as Glass, DiCaprio simply endures. He gives the movie a beating heart, offering it up, figuratively speaking, alive and bloody on a platter. It\u2014he\u2014is the most visceral effect in the movie: revenge served warm. Bon Appetite.\"<ref name=\"Stephanie Zacharek 2016, p54\"/> [[Richard Brody]] of ''[[The New Yorker]]'' was critical of the film, and said that [[Emmanuel Lubezki]]'s images were mere \"pictorial ornament[s] to [[Alejandro Gonz\u00e1lez I\u00f1\u00e1rritu|Alejandro G. I\u00f1\u00e1rritu's]] bland theatrical stagings.\"<ref name=\"SlantReview\">{{cite web|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/house/article/oscar-2016-winner-predictions-cinematography|title=Oscar 2016 Winner Predictions|publisher=Slant|accessdate=February 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\n''[[Slant Magazine]]''{{'}}s writer Ed Gonzalez suggested that the Slant staff in large part disliked the film: \"Our contempt for ''The Revenant'' knows no limits.\"<ref name=\"SlantReview\"/> Gonzalez unfavorably compared I\u00f1\u00e1rritu's work to [[Terrence Malick]]'s 2005 film ''[[The New World (2005 film)|The New World]]''. In the official review, Slant writer Jaime N. Christley wrote: \"''The Revenant'' [is] a misery-fest that plants its narrative flags as carelessly as a [[Roland Emmerich]] blockbuster, guaranteeing us a viewing experience almost as arduous as the trials depicted on screen, before reaching a conclusion that's sealed the moment audiences first meet the key players. After an obligatory false calm, ''The Revenant''{{'}}s proper opening scene is a show-stopping massacre at a fur-trapper's campsite. It's the kind of thing [[Howard Hawks]] would have handled\u2014and did, in ''[[The Big Sky (film)|The Big Sky]]''\u2014in under 90 seconds, with mostly off-camera particulars and minimal effects, but I\u00f1\u00e1rritu forces it to resemble the Normandy Beach sequence in ''[[Saving Private Ryan]]'' as much as history or sense will allow, and then some.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=The Revenant|url=https://www.slantmagazine.com/film/review/the-revenant-2015|publisher=Slant|accessdate=February 19, 2016}}</ref> ''The Revenant'' was ranked 22nd on [[Metacritic]]'s and 79th on [[Rotten Tomatoes]]' list of best films of 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/feature/film-critics-list-the-top-10-movies-of-2015|title=Best of 2015: Film Critic Top Ten Lists|website=Metacritic|accessdate=January 10, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/top/bestofrt/?year=2015|title=Top 100 Movies of 2015|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=December 16, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/article/critics-pick-the-best-films-and-performances-of-2015-in-indiewires-annual-poll-20151214|title=Critics Pick the Best Films and Performances of 2015 in Indiewire's Annual Poll|author=Steve Greene|work=[[Indiewire]]|date=December 14, 2015|accessdate=December 16, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{{main|List of accolades received by The Revenant}}\n[[File:Leonardo DiCaprio visited Goddard Saturday to discuss Earth science with Piers Sellers (26105091624) cropped.jpg|thumb|[[Leonardo DiCaprio]]'s performance was widely acclaimed and ultimately won him [[Academy Award for Best Actor|an Academy Award]], the first of his career after five previous nominations.]]\n\n''The Revenant'' has received numerous award nominations and wins, particularly for DiCaprio's performance, I\u00f1\u00e1rritu's direction and Lubezki's cinematography. At the [[88th Academy Awards|88th]] [[88th Academy Awards|Annual Academy Awards]], I\u00f1\u00e1rritu won the Best Director award for the second time in a row, [[Emmanuel Lubezki]] won for the third time in a row the award for [[Academy Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]] and DiCaprio won his first award for [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]]. Hardy lost the award for [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] to [[Mark Rylance]] for ''[[Bridge of Spies (film)|Bridge of Spies]]'', and the film itself lost [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]] to ''[[Spotlight (film)|Spotlight]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/oscar-nominations-2016-full-list-855670|title=Oscar Nominations: The Complete List|work=THR|date=January 14, 2016|accessdate=August 28, 2016}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[73rd Golden Globe Awards]] it won three awards: [[Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture \u2013 Drama|Best Motion Picture \u2013 Drama]], [[Golden Globe Award for Best Director|Best Director]], and [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Drama|Best Actor \u2013 Drama]]. It also had a nomination for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Score|Best Original Score]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/golden-globe-nominations-complete-list-847494/item/best-motion-picture-drama-golden-847480|title=Golden Globe Nominations: The Complete List|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=December 28, 2015}}</ref> On January 14, 2016, the film received 12 [[Academy Award]] nominations (more than any other film at the ceremony), including [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]] and [[Academy Award for Best Director|Best Director]] for I\u00f1\u00e1rritu, as well as [[Academy Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] and [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]], for DiCaprio and Hardy, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/oscar-nominations-2016-full-list-855670|title=Oscar Nominations: The Complete List|work=THR|date=January 14, 2016|accessdate=January 14, 2016}}</ref> On February 14, 2016, the film received the most awards at [[69th British Academy Film Awards]] out of eight-nominations, with five, including [[BAFTA Award for Best Film|Best Film]], [[BAFTA Award for Best Direction|Best Director]], [[BAFTA Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]], [[BAFTA Award for Best Sound|Best Sound]], and [[BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Leading Role|Best Leading Actor]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Baftas 2016: the nominations|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/film/movie-news/bafta-nominations-2016/|accessdate=January 8, 2016|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=January 8, 2016}}</ref> It received nine [[Critics' Choice Awards]] nominations, winning two&nbsp;\u2013 for DiCaprio as [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Actor|Best Actor]] and [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Cinematography|Best Cinematography]] for Lubezki.<ref name=officialnoms>{{cite web|url=http://www.criticschoice.com/movie-awards/ |title=Critics' Choice Awards |publisher=[[Broadcast Film Critics Association]] |accessdate=December 28, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6CrNMCA0g?url=http://www.criticschoice.com/movie-awards/ |archivedate=December 12, 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Tom Hardy]] won the [[London Film Critics' Circle Award for British Actor of the Year|Best British Actor]] award at the [[London Film Critics' Circle]] and was runner-up for [[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth Film Critics Association Award for Best Supporting Actor|Best Supporting Actor]] at [[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth Film Critics Association]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/in-contention/carol-45-years-and-tom-hardy-lead-london-critics-nominations-1201661539/|title='Carol,' '45 Years' Come Out On Top In London Critics' Award Nods|author=Lodge, Guy |work=Variety|accessdate=December 28, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dfwcritics.com/category/awards/|title=Awards|work=dfwcritics.com|accessdate=December 28, 2015}}</ref> DiCaprio was awarded [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Leading Role|Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Leading Role]] award at [[22nd Screen Actors Guild Awards]], while I\u00f1\u00e1rritu received [[Directors Guild of America Award for Outstanding Directing \u2013 Feature Film|Outstanding Directing \u2013 Feature Film]] award at [[68th Directors Guild of America Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dga.org/Awards/Annual.aspx|title=DGA Announces Nominees for Outstanding Directorial Achievement in Feature Film for 2015|publisher= [[Directors Guild of America]]|date=January 12, 2016|accessdate=January 12, 2016}}</ref> It received five [[20th Satellite Awards|Satellite Awards]] nominations, winning the award of [[Satellite Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture|Best Actor]] for DiCaprio.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/2015-satellite-award-nominees-announced-844739|title=2015 Satellite Award Nominees announced|last=Kilday| first=Gregg |date=December 1, 2015|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=December 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn May 2, 2016, ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine included both DiCaprio and I\u00f1\u00e1rritu in its issue of the 100 Most Influential People of 2015, with a cover photograph of DiCaprio on the magazine. [[John Kerry]], the U.S. Secretary of State, wrote a short testimonial to DiCaprio for this issue of ''Time'' stating that DiCaprio's dedication drives him to succeed and \"that's how he takes himself back 200 years to create an Oscar-winning, bear-brawling, powerhouse performance in ''The Revenant''.\"<ref>John Kerry. \"Leonardo DiCaprio:Earth's Leading Man\". TIME magazine, May 2, 2016, p 130.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Survival film]]\n* ''[[Man in the Wilderness]]'', a 1971 Western film loosely based on the Hugh Glass story\n* ''[[Lord Grizzly]]'', a 1954 biographical novel by [[Frederick Manfred]], about the Hugh Glass story\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em|refs=\n\n<!--<ref name=\"OfficialCast\">{{cite web | url= http://www.newregency.com/movies/the-revenant | title= The Revenant | author= Regency Staff | date= December 27, 2015 | work= Regency Enterprises | accessdate= December 28, 2015 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160103230252/http://www.newregency.com/movies/the-revenant# | archive-date= January 3, 2016 | url-status=dead | df= mdy-all }}</ref>-->\n\n<ref name=\"EllisonTalks\">{{cite web|last1=McNary|first1=Dave|title=Leonardo DiCaprio's Survival Drama 'The Revenant' Attracts Megan Ellison's Annapurna|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/news/leonardo-dicaprios-survival-drama-the-revenant-attracts-megan-ellisons-annapurna-1201261423/|work=Variety|accessdate=August 29, 2014|date=July 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"DiCaprioCast\">{{cite web|last1=Kit|first1=Borys|title=Leonardo DiCaprio, Alejandro Gonzalez Inarritu Team Up for 'Revenant'|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/leonardo-dicaprio-alejandro-gonzalez-inarritu-696259|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=August 29, 2014|date=April 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"InSequence\">{{cite web|last1=Chitwood|first1=Adam|title=The Revenant, Starring Leonardo DiCaprio and Tom Hardy, Gets Christmas 2015 Release Date; I\u00f1\u00e1rritu Hoping to Shoot in Sequence|url=https://collider.com/the-revenant-release-date/ |work=[[Collider (website)|Collider]] |accessdate=August 29, 2014|date=July 18, 2014}}</ref>\n\n<!--<ref name=\"Gleesonjoins\">{{cite web|author=RTE Staff|url=http://www.rte.ie/ten/news/2015/0720/716055-domhnall-gleeson-the-revenant/|title=Gleeson joins DiCaprio in The Revenant teaser|work=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann|RT\u00c9]]|date=July 20, 2015}}</ref>-->\n\n<ref name=\"Goldsman\">{{cite web| author = Vejvoda, Jim \"Stax\" | title=Akiva Goldsman Mauled by Grizzly! | url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2001/08/09/akiva-goldsman-mauled-by-grizzly | work=[[IGN]].com | accessdate = December 28, 2015 | date = August 9, 2001}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"BaleTalks\">{{cite web|last1=Miska|first1=Brad|title='Vacancy' Writer Pens 'Martyrs', Latest John Hillcoat Thriller!|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/20356/|work=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|accessdate=August 29, 2014|date=May 25, 2010}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"InarrituOn\">{{cite web|last1=Weinstein|first1=Joshua L.|title=Alejandro Gonzalez Inarritu Attached to Direct Warner's 'The Revenant' (Exclusive)|url=https://www.thewrap.com/movies/column-post/babel-director-alejandro-gonzalez-inarritu-attached-wbs-revenant-exclusive-30191/|work=TheWrap|accessdate=August 29, 2014|date=August 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"NewRegency\">{{cite web|last1=Abrams|first1=Rachel|title=New Regency boarding 'The Revenant'|url=https://variety.com/2011/film/news/new-regency-boarding-the-revenant-1118045396/|work=Variety|accessdate=August 29, 2014|date=November 1, 2011}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"DiCaprioPenn\">{{cite web|last1=Fleming, Jr.|first1=Mike|title=Leonardo DiCaprio, Sean Penn Wanted Men For New Regency's 'The Revenant'|url=https://deadline.com/2011/11/leonardo-dicaprio-sean-penn-wanted-men-for-new-regencys-the-revenant-191364/|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=August 29, 2014|date=November 4, 2011}}</ref>\n\n<ref